  <body>
    <main class="page">
      <header class="hero">
        <a class="home-link" href="/" aria-label="Back to home">sokolsky.me</a>
        <p class="eyebrow">Book notes · Eric Berne, 1964</p>
        <h1>Games People Play</h1>
        <p class="dek">
          Eric Berne gave names to arguments that seem spontaneous but somehow
          always end in the same place.
        </p>
      </header>

      <article class="article">
        <section id="bottom-line" aria-labelledby="bottom-line-heading">
          <h2 id="bottom-line-heading">Bottom line</h2>
          <p>
            Berne thinks a lot of social friction follows a script. One person says
            something plausible, a second message passes underneath and both
            people help steer the exchange toward a familiar ending. He calls the
            whole sequence a <em>game</em>. The payoff is often a bad feeling that
            confirms an old belief—Berne calls it the player’s <em>position</em>:
            “Everybody wants to deprive me,” “People can’t be trusted,” “All men
            are tyrants,” “I am blameless.”
          </p>
          <p>
            I found the names less useful than the sequences. Once an argument
            starts to feel weirdly rehearsed, it helps to look past its stated
            subject and trace what each person did to keep it going. Berne is much
            less convincing when he jumps from a memorable patient story to a
            general claim about why people behave as they do.
          </p>
          <blockquote>
            <p>
              <em>The book is good at spotting loops. It is a poor excuse for
              diagnosing whoever annoyed you this week.</em>
            </p>
          </blockquote>
        </section>

        <section id="model" aria-labelledby="model-heading">
          <h2 id="model-heading">The model in five minutes</h2>
          <p>
            Berne begins with three <em>ego states</em>: coherent systems of
            feeling tied to matching sets of behavior, all of them available in
            any person. They are not ages, roles or moral rankings; in this
            system, Berne insists, “there is no such thing as an ‘immature
            person’”—only moments when the wrong state holds the wheel.
          </p>
          <div class="ego-states" aria-label="The three ego states">
            <div class="ego-state">
              <p class="state-letter" aria-hidden="true">P</p>
              <h3>Parent</h3>
              <p>
                Reproduces one’s actual parents. It raises children and runs
                routine matters automatically (“that’s the way it’s done”),
                freeing the Adult from trivial decisions—but it also nags and
                forbids in an inherited voice.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div class="ego-state">
              <p class="state-letter" aria-hidden="true">A</p>
              <h3>Adult</h3>
              <p>
                Processes data and computes probabilities, like judging when to
                cross a busy highway. It deals with present reality and mediates
                between the other two states.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div class="ego-state">
              <p class="state-letter" aria-hidden="true">C</p>
              <h3>Child</h3>
              <p>
                A relic of the actual child one once was, fixated early and
                still active. In it reside intuition, creativity, spontaneous
                drive and enjoyment—and also whining, rebellion and compliance.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <p>
            A <em>transaction</em> is one unit of social exchange: a stimulus and a
            response. Berne’s example: “Do you know where my cuff links are?”
            followed by “On the desk” is a complementary Adult-to-Adult
            transaction, and talk proceeds smoothly. “Do you know where my cuff
            links are?” followed by “You always blame me for everything” is a
            <em>crossed</em> transaction: an Adult question receives a Child
            response aimed at a Parent, and communication breaks off until the
            lines realign. The cuff links have to wait.
          </p>
          <p>
            The third kind powers games: the <em>ulterior</em> transaction, which
            runs on two levels at once. A salesman says, “This one is better, but
            you can’t afford it”—Adult words on the surface, a hook to the
            customer’s Child underneath. She answers the hidden message: “That’s
            the one I’ll take.”
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="social-time" aria-labelledby="social-time-heading">
          <h2 id="social-time-heading">How people structure time</h2>
          <p>
            Berne starts from three hungers: for stimulation, for recognition
            and for structure—something to do with the hours between “hello” and
            death. Alone, a person can fill time with activity or fantasy. In
            company, Berne lists the options in order of complexity:
          </p>
          <ol class="ladder">
            <li>
              <strong>Rituals</strong>
              <span>Fixed, tradition-programmed exchanges: greetings, courtesies, an “eight-stroke” hello.</span>
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Pastimes</strong>
              <span>Semi-ritual small talk around one topic—“General Motors” (comparing cars), “PTA,” “Wardrobe”—used to fill time and audition partners for games.</span>
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Games</strong>
              <span>Repetitive exchanges with a concealed level and a payoff.</span>
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Intimacy</strong>
              <span>Direct, candid, game-free contact without a concealed bargain.</span>
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Activity</strong>
              <span>Work on external reality; a matrix any of the others can grow inside.</span>
            </li>
          </ol>
          <p>
            Each form provides <em>strokes</em>, Berne’s unit of recognition—his
            colloquial axiom is “if you are not stroked, your spinal cord will
            shrivel up.” A compliment is a stroke; so is an insult. He cites rat
            experiments in which gentle handling and painful electric shocks were
            equally effective at keeping the animals healthy. People settle for
            painful strokes on the same logic: any recognition beats none, and
            they know how to obtain the insult reliably.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="anatomy" aria-labelledby="anatomy-heading">
          <h2 id="anatomy-heading">Anatomy of a game</h2>
          <p>
            Berne’s definition: “an ongoing series of complementary ulterior
            transactions progressing to a well-defined, predictable outcome…
            or, more colloquially, a series of moves with a snare, or
            ‘gimmick.’” Unlike a ritual or a pastime, a game is “basically
            dishonest, and the outcome has a dramatic, as distinct from merely
            exciting, quality.” Crucially, he is describing unconscious games
            played by people who are not fully aware of the second level—not
            deliberate manipulation.
          </p>
          <div class="sequence" aria-label="Sequence of a psychological game">
            <div>
              <span>1</span>
              <p><strong>Con</strong><br />An opening move that looks straightforward but carries a hidden invitation.</p>
            </div>
            <div>
              <span>2</span>
              <p><strong>Gimmick</strong><br />A weakness in the other person that makes them answer the hidden message.</p>
            </div>
            <div>
              <span>3</span>
              <p><strong>Switch</strong><br />At a familiar cue, one player changes ego states and the stated subject drops away.</p>
            </div>
            <div>
              <span>4</span>
              <p><strong>Payoff</strong><br />A surprise feeling that lands everyone in a familiar position.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <p>
            Berne wrote the tidy formula down later—Con + Gimmick = Response →
            Switch → Payoff—and James R. Allen’s 2011 introduction illustrates
            it with a mother who finds a vase shattered, knows perfectly well
            the dog is outside, and still asks five-year-old Johnny “Who did
            that?” The question is an invitation to lie. “Doggie,” he says. Her
            neck reddens, she switches from Adult to Parent and hits him: “I
            will not have a child who lies!” Her payoff is righteous wrath—a
            round of “Now I’ve Got You”; his is feeling kicked. Had he said “I
            did it,” there would have been no game.
          </p>
          <p>
            Games survive because every player gets something from them, even when
            the result is unpleasant. Berne itemizes the advantages for each game
            he catalogs: strokes, avoided fears, structured hours and—always—the
            confirmation of a position taken in childhood.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="games" aria-labelledby="games-heading">
          <h2 id="games-heading">The most useful games to recognize</h2>
          <div class="game-list">
            <article>
              <h3>Why Don’t You—Yes But</h3>
              <p>
                The first game Berne dissected, and the origin of the whole
                theory. Someone presents a problem; others offer solutions; each
                gets a “Yes, but…” The purpose is not to get suggestions but to
                reject them—the payoff is the crestfallen silence when everyone
                gives up, proving no one can help.
              </p>
              <p class="exit"><strong>Berne’s exit:</strong> don’t play adviser. “That is a difficult problem. What are you going to do about it?”</p>
            </article>
            <article>
              <h3>If It Weren’t for You</h3>
              <p>
                The most common game between spouses. Mrs. White complains her
                domineering husband blocks her—yet when therapy loosened his
                grip and she signed up for dancing lessons, she discovered a
                morbid fear of dance floors. The restriction she protests is one
                her Child shrewdly arranged.
              </p>
              <p class="exit"><strong>Berne’s exit:</strong> permissiveness. The game runs on “Don’t you dare”; “Go ahead!” unmasks the fear.</p>
            </article>
            <article>
              <h3>Now I’ve Got You, You Son of a Bitch</h3>
              <p>
                A plumber overruns an agreed quote by four dollars on a
                four-hundred-dollar job, and White erupts with the pent-up fury
                of years. The injustice is not the prize; the long-awaited
                license to prosecute is. In poker: holding four aces and caring
                less about the pot than that the opponent is at your mercy.
              </p>
              <p class="exit"><strong>Berne’s exit:</strong> correct behavior—explicit terms up front, strict adherence, and graceful yielding on surprises.</p>
            </article>
            <article>
              <h3>See What You Made Me Do</h3>
              <p>
                Absorbed in a task, White is interrupted; the interruption
                “causes” his chisel to slip, and he turns on the visitor in
                rage. It is his own irritation that caused the slip, and he is
                glad it happened: the family learns to leave him alone, which
                was the point. Deferring decisions sets up the harder form:
                whatever goes wrong, “You got me into this.”
              </p>
              <p class="exit"><strong>Berne’s exit:</strong> leave him alone—or hand the decision back and let him keep it.</p>
            </article>
            <article>
              <h3>Kick Me</h3>
              <p>
                A man whose social manner amounts to wearing a sign that reads
                “Please Don’t Kick Me.” The temptation is almost irresistible;
                when the natural result follows, he cries, “Why does this always
                happen to me?” If bystanders restrain themselves, he escalates
                until they oblige.
              </p>
              <p class="exit"><strong>Exit:</strong> don’t kick—and examine the move made just before the predictable rejection.</p>
            </article>
            <article>
              <h3>I’m Only Trying to Help You</h3>
              <p>
                A helper gives advice that fails, tries again, and is finally met
                with fury—“Look what you made me do!” His bewilderment at the
                ingratitude is the payoff, confirming that people are
                disappointing. Success would actually threaten the position, so
                it quietly invites sabotage.
              </p>
              <p class="exit"><strong>Berne’s exit:</strong> a plain Adult contract—“I think we can do something about it”—with no need for the client to stay sick.</p>
            </article>
            <article>
              <h3>Schlemiel</h3>
              <p>
                A guest spills a highball on the hostess’s gown, burns the
                tablecloth, grinds gravy into the rug—then says “I’m sorry.” The
                messes are pleasures along the way; the real payoff is the
                forgiveness the apology extracts.
              </p>
              <p class="exit"><strong>Berne’s exit:</strong> “Tonight you can wreck the rug—but please don’t say ‘I’m sorry.’”</p>
            </article>
            <article>
              <h3>Blemish</h3>
              <p>
                Played from the depressive position “I am no good,” protectively
                converted into “They are no good.” The player cannot relax with a
                new person until the flaw is found—last year’s hat, hasn’t read
                Rilke—and finding it wards off both depression and the intimacy
                that might expose his own blemishes.
              </p>
              <p class="exit"><strong>Exit:</strong> notice when accurate criticism is doing the work of keeping someone safely dismissible.</p>
            </article>
            <article>
              <h3>Uproar</h3>
              <p>
                Fault-finding answered by impudence, voices rising, and an
                ending marked by a slamming door. Berne’s classic case is a
                domineering father and teenage daughter; the quarrel lets two
                people live together while guaranteeing distance—the slammed
                doors emphasize the separate bedrooms.
              </p>
              <p class="exit"><strong>Exit:</strong> decline the escalation; the fight is the intimacy-avoidance, not a detour from it.</p>
            </article>
            <article>
              <h3>Wooden Leg</h3>
              <p>
                “What do you expect of a man with a wooden leg?” A real,
                exaggerated or imaginary limitation becomes a blanket exemption
                from trying—the dramatic form being the plea of insanity. A
                literate player has no trouble finding authorities to support
                the plea.
              </p>
              <p class="exit"><strong>Berne’s exit:</strong> “I don’t expect anything. The question is, what do you expect of yourself?”</p>
            </article>
          </div>
        </section>

        <section id="degrees" aria-labelledby="degrees-heading">
          <h2 id="degrees-heading">Not every game is equally serious</h2>
          <p>
            Berne grades games by intensity. A first-degree game is socially
            acceptable in the player’s circle. A second-degree game does no
            permanent damage, but the players would rather conceal it from the
            public. A third-degree game is “played for keeps,” ending in the
            surgery, the courtroom or the morgue. The same pattern scales: Rapo
            runs from party flirtation, through indignant rejection, to a
            courtroom accusation.
          </p>
          <p>
            Calling all three “patterns” can blur differences in harm. An awkward
            recurring conversation does not belong in the same category as abuse,
            addiction or violence.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="using-it" aria-labelledby="using-it-heading">
          <h2 id="using-it-heading">How to use the book without becoming unbearable</h2>
          <ul class="questions">
            <li>
              <strong>Start with your own payoff.</strong> Naming somebody else’s
              “game” is often just a sophisticated move in a new game.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Describe the sequence, not the person.</strong> “We reject
              every proposed solution” is more useful than “You’re playing Why
              Don’t You—Yes But.”
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Check the social and psychological levels.</strong> What is
              being said openly? What response is being invited underneath?
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Look for the switch.</strong> At what moment does a normal
              exchange turn into confusion, accusation or helplessness?
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Return to Adult.</strong> State the observable issue, ask a
              direct question and make responsibility explicit.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Offer a non-game alternative.</strong> A pattern weakens
              when the underlying need can be expressed without the trap.
            </li>
          </ul>
        </section>

        <section id="dated" aria-labelledby="dated-heading">
          <h2 id="dated-heading">What has not aged well</h2>
          <p>
            A lot of the book reads like 1964 because it is. Games are described
            “from the male point of view unless they are clearly feminine,” and
            the feminine ones carry titles like “Frigid Woman” and “Harried”
            (the overloaded housewife), with dynamics attributed to penis envy.
            Homosexuality is discussed as a game and a pathology. The chapter on
            “Alcoholic” declares that “in game analysis there is no such thing
            as alcoholism,” only a role in a game—and that a true cure means the
            former Alcoholic “should be able to drink socially.” Modern
            addiction medicine says otherwise.
          </p>
          <p>
            Berne also generalizes freely from memorable cases: he floats
            schizophrenia as a child’s countermove to the family game of
            “Corner,” sketches an “Asthma Game” as an etiological factor, and
            assigns each game a tidy Freudian engine (“anal aggression,” “oral
            deprivation”). The recurring sequence, hidden message and payoff are
            things a reader can watch for; his explanations of what caused them
            are often guesses, and the labels become silly fast when treated as
            final answers.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="beyond" aria-labelledby="beyond-heading">
          <h2 id="beyond-heading">Beyond games</h2>
          <p>
            Berne calls the alternative <em>autonomy</em>. He breaks it into three
            capacities:
          </p>
          <dl class="autonomy">
            <div>
              <dt>Awareness</dt>
              <dd>“The capacity to see a coffeepot and hear the birds sing in one’s own way, and not the way one was taught”—living here and now rather than at the office door one is driving toward.</dd>
            </div>
            <div>
              <dt>Spontaneity</dt>
              <dd>Option: the freedom to choose one’s feelings from the whole assortment—Parent, Adult and Child—instead of having only the feelings one was taught to have.</dd>
            </div>
            <div>
              <dt>Intimacy</dt>
              <dd>The spontaneous, game-free candidness of an aware person; contact without a concealed bargain.</dd>
            </div>
          </dl>
          <p>
            Getting there, Berne says, amounts to “obtaining a friendly divorce
            from one’s parents… so that they may be agreeably visited on
            occasion, but are no longer dominant.” Parent and Child remain part
            of the person; autonomy means having some choice about who answers.
            He is not optimistic about the species—the closing chapter concedes
            that “there is no hope for the human race, but there is hope for
            individual members of it.”
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="sources" aria-labelledby="sources-heading">
          <h2 id="sources-heading">Sources and edition note</h2>
          <p>
            This summary is based on the 2011 Tantor eBook,
            <cite>Games People Play: The Basic Handbook of Transactional Analysis</cite>,
            which includes James R. Allen’s 2011 introduction and Kurt Vonnegut’s
            review from the June 11, 1965 issue of <cite>Life</cite>. All quotes
            are from that edition. Publication context and terminology were
            cross-checked against the <a href="https://ericberne.com/games-people-play/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Eric Berne family site’s book guide</a>
            and its <a href="https://ericberne.com/transactional-analysis/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">introduction to transactional analysis</a>.
            Berne and his friends had to pool their money to get the book
            published in 1964; it became a runaway bestseller anyway.
          </p>
        </section>
      </article>
    </main>
  </body>
